@* CASCADING PARAMETER (decision 134). <CascadingValue> hands a value to EVERY descendant that asks
   for it by TYPE, without each intervening component having to declare and forward it.

   The lowering: because composition inlines every child into ONE mount(), a cascade is nothing more
   than LEXICAL SCOPE. The cascaded expression is the parent's own, already in scope at the point the
   descendant is inlined, so a [CascadingParameter] read compiles to that expression directly. There
   is no context object, no dictionary, and no subscription.

   DOM contract: #depth is rendered by the child, from a value the PARENT cascaded and never passed
   as an attribute. Clicking #inc must move it 1 -> 2 -- a cascade that resolved once at mount would
   sit at "1"; that update is the measurement (BENCH n°53). *@

<div id="wrap"><CascadingValue Value="@level"><Gauge /></CascadingValue><button id="inc" @onclick="Inc">inc</button></div>

@code {
    private int level = 1;
    void Inc() { level++; }
}
